"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389669","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-21","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills has not held a meeting with either the Low Pay Commission or the Centre for Research in Social Policy to discuss the National Living Wage.</p><p>However, the Low Pay Commission has been asked to provide a report to the Prime Minister and Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills regarding the level of the National Living Wage in the future. This report should provide an assessment of the pace of increase to reach the Government’s ambition of 60% of median earnings by 2020. In making its recommendations on the National Minimum Wage, the Low Pay Commission takes into account a wide range of evidence from across the economy. This process will continue for the National Living Wage too.</p><p>As leaders of the Minimum Income Standard programme, which forms the basis for setting the Living Wage, the Centre for Research in Social Policy are welcome and encouraged to provide evidence during the Low Pay Commission’s public consultation regarding future rates.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-21T13:51:54.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389669/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389669/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with the (a) Low Pay Commission and (b) Centre for Research in Social Policy at Loughborough University on the National Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","6931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389670","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-21","<p /> <p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills consulted on Support for Postgraduate Study in spring 2015, proposing a loan system to overcome financial barriers to accessing postgraduate taught Master’s, and to review support for postgraduate research. The consultation response is currently being analysed and the Department will respond in the autumn.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-07-21T15:29:50.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389670/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389670/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Postgraduate Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to improve access to postgraduate education.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","6935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389671","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-20","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Details of Ministers’ meetings with external organisations are published quarterly on the Gov.uk website:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-business-innovation-skills&amp;publication_type=transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-business-innovation-skills&amp;publication_type=transparency-data</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-07-20T15:34:04.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389671/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389671/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many times (a) he and (b) other Ministers in his Department met employees or third-party representatives of tobacco companies in (i) 2013, (ii) 2014 and (iii) 2015.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","7010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389672","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-20","<p>All consumer products including virtual reality headsets are covered by the General Product Safety Regulations 2005 which implements the EU’s General Product Safety Directive. The regulations impose requirements concerning the safety of products ensuring that only safe products are placed on the market.</p><p> </p><p>It is the obligation of the producer to hold appropriate documentation such as test results and risk assessments to show that their products are safe. The Department does not hold this information.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-20T15:21:14.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389672/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389672/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Virtual Reality Headsets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what information his Department holds on the tests and risk assessments that are used to ensure that users of virtual reality headsets will not suffer eye damage.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","7066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389674","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-20","<p /> <p>The Department has not made an estimate of the number of virtual reality headsets sold in the UK.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-20T15:20:23.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389674/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389674/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Virtual Reality Headsets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department made an estimate of the number of virtual reality headsets that have been sold in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","7065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389675","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-21","<p>The UK Government supports an extension of the transition period for least developed countries (LDCs) to comply with certain obligations regarding pharmaceutical products under the World Trade Organisation’s Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPS) Agreement. Extending the transitional arrangements for a time-bound period will allow LDCs time to ensure their intellectual property laws and practices conform with the TRIPS Agreement. Stimulating innovation and growth in LDCs is key, and we are working to encourage all countries to establish high quality intellectual property protection and enforcement frameworks to facilitate economic growth and participation in world trade.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-21T14:33:48.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389675/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389675/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Drugs: Developing Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department supports the request by the Least-Developed Countries (LDC) group at the World Trade Organisation for an extension of the transition period to utilise trade-related aspects of intellectual property rights' flexibilities relating to pharmaceutical products for as long as those countries remain an LDC.","false","Biography information for Mike Freer","Finchley and Golders Green","Mike Freer","7074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389677","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-20","<p>The CE marking indicates that a product complies with one or more pieces of EU Single Market legislation. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills works with businesses, including small businesses, to support them in meeting the requirements of the legislation, for example by producing guidance, working with trade associations to raise awareness, and engaging directly with businesses to solve specific issues. In addition, I will continue to press the European Commission to identify opportunities to reduce the burden of complying with Single Market legislation, particularly for SMEs, wherever possible.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-20T15:35:35.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389677/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389677/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Small Businesses: Certification Quality Marks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to support small businesses to produce products which comply with CE marking standards; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","7116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389678","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Government is committed to implementing ‘<em>Building a Prosperous and United Community</em>’, the Economic Pact between the Government and the Northern Ireland Executive which aims to help rebalance the economy and build a more united and stronger society. As part of this, my officials have held discussions with the Northern Ireland Executive to progress a range of matters, such as measures to improve access to finance, reduce regulatory burdens and support innovation.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-20T15:32:13.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389678/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389678/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Economic Growth: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in the Northern Ireland Assembly on ensuing business growth in the Northern Ireland economy.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","7091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389679","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-20","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The CE marking indicates that a product complies with one or more pieces of EU Single Market legislation. The cost of compliance for small businesses therefore varies significantly depending on which legislation applies, and reflects factors such as the complexity of the product and the risks associated with it. Whilst I have not made a specific assessment of these costs at an aggregate level, I will continue to press the European Commission to identify opportunities to reduce the burden of complying with Single Market legislation, particularly for SMEs, wherever possible.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-20T16:34:27.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389679/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389679/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Small Businesses: Certification Quality Marks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the effect on small businesses of them meeting CE marking requirements on their products; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","7143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389680","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-21","<p>National Vocational Qualifications (NVQs) are regulated qualifications. Skills policy is a devolved matter. In England, Ofqual recognises awarding organisations which offer regulated qualifications (including NVQs). Ofqual requires recognised awarding organisations to comply with its General Conditions of Recognition. These Conditions require that qualifications must be fit for purpose and accurately and reliably assessed. Ofqual reviews the extent to which awarding organisations comply with the Conditions and it has a range of powers it may use if an organisation is not complying.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-21T13:47:44.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389680/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389680/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","National Vocational Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to evaluate the accuracy of NVQ assessments.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","7125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389682","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-17","<p>An itemised year-by-year breakdown of the Inquiry’s costs can be found on the Inquiry’s website. (<a href="http://www.iraqinquiry.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.iraqinquiry.org.uk</a>)</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-07-17T09:15:00.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389682/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389682/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-14","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the (a) costs and (b) fees incurred have been of the Chilcot Inquiry in each year to date since the setting up of that inquiry.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","7127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389684","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-22","<p>The Government will continue to ensure that the House of Lords functions effectively, and will consider how to address issues such as the number of peers in the House.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-07-22T15:09:28.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389684/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389684/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-14","House of Lords: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans the Government has to reduce the number of peers in the House of Lords.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","7157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389685","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-21","<p>There are currently two cross-departmental review processes being run by the Cabinet Office. The first is focussed on National Security, refreshing the 2010 National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review. The second is the Bribery and Corruption enforcement review.</p><p> </p><p>The next iteration of the National Security Strategy and the Strategic Defence and Security Review will cover reserved matters. The Cabinet Office plans to consult a wide range of stakeholders, including the Devolved Administrations.</p><p> </p><p>The Bribery and Corruption enforcement review has consulted widely, including with relevant agencies of the Devolved Administrations. These include the National Counter Corruption Unit of Police Scotland, and the Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service.</p><p> </p><p>There are also a number of cross-departmental review processes being run, for example the ‘Cutting Red Tape’ programme and the Resilience Review. These reviews consult widely, including with relevant agencies of the Devolved Administrations where appropriate, usually via the Lead Government Departments.</p><p> </p><p>I will write to the Honourable Member in the Autumn to provide a more detailed update of the cross-departmental review processes being undertaken by the Cabinet Office, and will place a copy of this letter in the library of the House.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2015-07-21T17:15:23.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389685/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389685/answer","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389685/answer/previousversion/16272","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-14","Government Departments: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what cross-departmental reviews are being undertaken by his Department; and what the extent and nature of the engagement with the devolved administrations is for each such review.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","7169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389686","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-20","<p>Requests for Major Projects Authority reports are considered on a case by case basis, with the underlying understanding that reviews need to take place within a safe space, without the expectation of imminent publication, to be sufficiently probing and effective.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-07-20T15:27:40.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389686/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389686/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-14","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what guidance his Department provides to other departments on the publication of OGC Gateway Reviews.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","7085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389688","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-20","<p>Information on youth service expenditure by local authority is collected by the Department for Education and published on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>. Data is not collected on a per capita basis.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-07-20T16:37:42.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389688/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389688/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-14","Youth Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the (a) absolute and (b) proportionate change in expenditure per capita on youth services was in each local authority area between 2012-13 and 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Ms Karen Buck","Westminster North","Ms Karen Buck","6978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389690","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-20","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","6899","2015-07-20T08:36:54.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389690/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389690/answer","PQs 6899 and 6903.pdf","PQs 6899 and 6903.pdf","UKSA Reply","UKSA Reply","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389690/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-14","Living Wage: Woking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of employees were paid less than the living wage in (a) Woking constituency and (b) England in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","6903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389692","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-20","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","6903","2015-07-20T08:36:54.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389692/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389692/answer","PQs 6899 and 6903.pdf","PQs 6899 and 6903.pdf","UKSA Reply","UKSA Reply","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389692/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-14","Minimum Wage: Woking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many (a) full-time and (b) part-time employees were paid the minimum wage in Woking constituency in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","6899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389697","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-20","<p>On 8 July the Government published the 2015 remit for the Low Pay Commission, which sets out their role in relation to the National Living Wage and the National Minimum Wage rates. A copy of the remit can be found on the GOV.UK website</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-20T15:31:04.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389697/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389697/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Low Pay Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he plans to publish revised Terms of Reference for the Low Pay Commission.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","6963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389699","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-20","<p>The income threshold after which payments of Child Tax Credit begin to be reduced will continue to depend on a number of factors: the first income threshold (the Working Tax Credit threshold), the taper rate (the rate at which tax credits are reduced once the first income threshold has been exceeded), and the level of uprating of the individual elements of tax credits.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-07-20T13:48:43.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389699/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389699/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on changing the income threshold for child tax credit (a) in 2016-17 and (b) by 2020.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","6966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389701","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-20","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government has announced a new mandatory National Living Wage for all workers aged 25 and over, to be introduced at £7.20 from April 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Low Pay Commission considers carefully the economic conditions in sectors and different geographic areas when developing its recommendations to Government on the National Minimum Wage. It publishes this analysis each year. However, the Government has no plans to ask the Low Pay Commission to publish a review of separate wage-floors that could be applied in London.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The simplicity of the National Minimum Wage – its UK-wide coverage – is crucial to its success. Having a UK wide National Minimum Wage provides clarity for employers, particularly those who operate across the UK and all of its sectors.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-20T15:28:08.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389701/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389701/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Pay: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will ask the Low Pay Commission to (a) publish an analysis of which sectors of the UK economy could afford to increase wages above the new statutory minimum and (b) carry out a review of a separate wage-floor that could be applied in London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","6964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389703","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-20","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government has announced a new mandatory National Living Wage to be introduced at £7.20 in April 2016 for those aged 25 and over. The Government has set out the ambition that this should continue to increase to reach 60% of median earnings by 2020, subject to sustained economic growth.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-20T15:24:29.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389703/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389703/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Low Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what target he has set for reducing the number of employees who earn below two-thirds of the median hourly wage.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","6965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389704","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-20","<p>No discussions have taken place between UK and Scottish Ministers on this specific issue. The decision on whether to make available NHS Scotland data to support the identification process for Scottish taxpayers is one for the Scottish Government. HMRC plans to use a variety of data sources to ensure that the identification is as accurate as possible; however HMRC’s process for identifying Scottish taxpayers does not rely on having access to this information.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-07-20T16:23:14.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389704/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389704/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Taxpayers: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with Ministers of the Scottish Government on the use of NHS Scotland's Central Register to identify Scottish taxpayers.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","7086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389705","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-22","<p>The reason for the apparent discrepancy is that the documents refer to two separate figures in two separate budgets. Paragraph 2.113 of Budget 2015 allocated £75 million. Paragraph 2.47 of Summer Budget 2015 allocated a further £70 million of banking fines to military charities and good causes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This takes it to a total of £145m committed in this calendar year.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-07-22T15:03:26.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389705/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389705/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","LIBOR","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the reason is for the apparent disparity between paragraph 2.113 of Budget 2015, which states that the government has committed £75 million of LIBOR fines over the next five years to support military charities and other good causes and paragraph 2.47 of Summer Budget 2015, which states that the government has committed nearly £70 million of banking fines over the next five years to support military charities and other good causes.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","7100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389706","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-21","<p>The UK’s monetary policy framework, set out in the Bank of England Act 1998 gives operational responsibility for monetary policy to the independent Monetary Policy Committee (MPC). Decisions on the use of monetary policy tools, including quantitative easing, are for the judgement of the MPC.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-07-21T14:53:12.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389706/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389706/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Monetary Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the criteria under which assets issued as a result of the quantitative easing programme would be bought back.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","7046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389707","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-21","<p>The UK’s monetary policy framework, set out in the Bank of England Act 1998, gives operational responsibility for monetary policy to the independent Monetary Policy Committee (MPC). Decisions on the use of monetary policy tools, including quantitative easing, are for the judgement of the MPC.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-07-21T14:54:40.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389707/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389707/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Monetary Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he expects further quantitative easing to be undertaken in the next three years.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","7047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389709","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-21","<p>In 2010 the government established the Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) to provide independent and authoritative analysis of the UK’s public finances.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The OBR forecast in July 2015 that potential productivity will grow by 1.4 per cent in 2015, 1.8 per cent in 2016, 2.0 per cent in 2017, 2.1 per cent in 2018 and 2.2 per cent thereafter.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-07-21T14:41:07.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389709/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389709/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the sustainable rate of productive potential in the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","7048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389710","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Government will make a capital contribution of $3.1bn (£2bn) to the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank, to support much needed infrastructure investment in Asia and in turn increase global growth. 20% of this capital will be paid in and 80% of this capital will be callable. The paid in contribution will be made in five equal annual instalments with the first payment of $122.2mn (£80mn) in FY2015/16.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-07-20T15:28:20.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389710/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389710/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 13 July 2015 to Question 6124, what level of capital contribution will be made to the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank in (a) 2015 and (b) each of the following four years.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","7016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389712","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Barnett Formula was applied in the usual way to changes in departmental spending at Summer Budget 2015. As a result the Northern Ireland Executive will receive £3 million in additional allocations.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-07-20T16:25:23.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389712/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389712/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Block Grant: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what changes in the block grant to Northern Ireland will arise as a result of the Summer Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","7017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389714","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-20","<p>As set out in paragraph 1.213 of the Summer Budget Report, the responses to the consultation on introducing a tobacco levy will be published shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-07-20T13:43:08.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389714/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389714/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Tobacco: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will instruct HM Revenue and Customs to publish its analysis of the design and potential effects of the proposed tobacco levy.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","7008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389715","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-22","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at: http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-07-22T15:04:10.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389715/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389715/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had on the apprenticeship levy with (a) businesses, (b) the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, (c) the Secretary of State for Education and (d) organisations representing industry.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","6930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389716","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-22","<p>The Data Protection Act 1998 (DPA) requires every data controller who is processing personal information to register with the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) unless they are exempt. Failure to do so is a criminal offence.</p><p> </p><p>The ICO has the ability to prosecute data controllers who process personal data having failed to notify in accordance with the DPA. A successful prosecution could result in a fine being imposed. The length of time that a data controller has failed to notify, and any financial benefit they have received from not paying the notification fees, is a factor that is taken into account by the Court when sentencing and setting the appropriate level of fine. There are no provisions in the Proceeds of Crime Act that would require someone to report to a court or anyone else that any profit has been made from the offence of processing personal data without being registered. If someone suspects that money laundering has occurred then the reporting obligations set out in the Money Laundering Regulations 2007 will, for example, apply.</p><p> </p><p>It is for data controllers to seek registration; the ICO periodically reminds organisations of the requirement to notify. Fee income has been increasing year on year with increasing numbers of notifications.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice and the ICO are looking at the current funding model as part of negotiations on the proposed EU Data Protection Regulation.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","6947 ; 6948 ; 6949 ; 6951 ; 6952 ; 7446","2015-07-22T10:07:55.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389716/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389716/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-14","Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the extent of revenue that has been lost to the public purse in each of the last seven financial years as a result of data controllers who are required to notify or register under the Data Protection Act and pay a fee not doing so; and what steps he is taking to (a) recoup the losses to the public purse that have occurred and (b) prevent such further losses.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Marie Rimmer","6938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389718","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-22","<p>The Information Commissioner is responsible for determining the pay and conditions of his staff and in doing so must comply with the principles of Managing Public Money and Civil Service Pay Guidance.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2015-07-22T11:27:01.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389718/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389718/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-14","Information Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the level of remuneration of Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) personnel based in the ICO's Wilmslow office and the requests made to increase such remuneration; and whether meeting such requests would require a relaxation of existing pay restraint policies.","false","Biography information for Ms Marie Rimmer","St Helens South and Whiston","Marie Rimmer","6939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389720","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-22","<p>To support connectivity in the South West, the government will allocate up to £10m to the broadband programme in the South West, commencing April 2016. The fund will be available for local projects to bid into, with priority given to those delivering ultrafast speeds of 100mbps and above. Broadband Delivery UK will start working with local projects immediately to determine the most effective way of delivering support.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This scheme begins in the financial year 2016-17, budgets for this year and beyond will be set at the forthcoming Spending Review. Government is working to determine the most effective way of delivering support, with further details published in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-07-22T15:02:21.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389720/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389720/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.318 of the Summer Budget 2015, HC 264, from which budget has the £10 million expenditure on broadband been found; how many more premises will be reached by broadband as a result of that expenditure; and whether national projects will be ineligible to bid for that expenditure.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","6979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389721","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-21","<p /> <p>The levy will apply to all larger employers in the UK.</p><p>I also refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 17<sup>th</sup> July to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-07-09/6449/" target="_blank">6449</a>.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-21T13:46:43.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389721/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389721/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-14","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether he plans for the proposed apprenticeship levy only to apply to private companies.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","6980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389723","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-22","<p>The majority of the recipient charities and good causes mentioned in paragraph 2.47 of the Summer Budget 2015 are Defence related and can be considered to be “National”. The exceptions being:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Ludlow Museum £0.25 million – to facilitate the publication online of the unique and historically important geological collections held in Ludlow - Ludlow;</p><p> </p></li><li><p>regeneration of the National Memorial Arboretum £2 million – to protect the long term future of the Memorial and to preserve it for the next generation – Lichfield;</p></li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Clock Tower Foundation £3 million – to provide a bespoke rehabilitation centre to support the Special Forces – North Herefordshire; and</p></li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Battle of Britain Bunker £1 million – to renovate and maintain the Battle of Britain Operations Room at RAF Uxbridge which coordinated the air defence of London and the South of England in WWII – Uxbridge.</p><p> </p></li></ul><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-07-22T16:24:18.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389723/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389723/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Banks: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, in which parliamentary constituency each project referred to in paragraph 2.47 of the Summer Budget 2015 is based.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","6991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389725","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-20","<p>Controlled Foreign Company (CFC) rules are designed to protect the UK tax base by preventing multinational groups based in the UK from diverting their UK profits artificially to companies in low tax jurisdictions to reduce their UK tax bill. They work by charging UK tax on those profits and so act as a deterrent to this behaviour.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government reformed the Controlled Foreign Company (CFC) rules after close consultation with stakeholders in 2012. This was the first substantial revision to the rules since their introduction in 1984.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This modernised CFC regime, which took effect in 2013, is closely targeted on artificially diverted profits to protect the UK tax base while reflecting modern global business practices.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Summer Budget also announced strengthening of the CFC rules to tackle aggressive tax planning by preventing UK based multinationals offsetting their losses against the UK’s CFC tax on profits they divert from the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As with all aspects of the tax system, the Government will keep this legislation under review, and will act to prevent abuse of these rules.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-07-20T15:47:05.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389725/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389725/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-14","Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the changes to CFC rules introduced in the 2010 Emergency Budget on corporation tax receipts in each year of the last Parliament.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","6982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389726","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>No detailed decisions have been taken yet on the annual budget allocations for the £90 million extension of the Coastal Community Fund to 2020-21. Future funding arrangements will be considered as part of the 2015 Spending Review.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-07-21T15:51:50.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389726/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/389726/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-14","Coastal Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraph 2.30 of the Summer Budget 2015, how much funding has been assigned to the Coastal Communities Fund in each fiscal year to 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","6992"
